title: For Sale/Trade:  Rare Finnish M39 Mosin Nagant
postcontent:
Note: some local guy who is pissed at me for selling this has called it ultra rare, himself. I'm not sure about that. I just think it's rare. Haters gonna hate. Here's my offer and why:

Classic Firearms has sold off the last known batch of Finnish M39 rifles and I was lucky to grab a beautiful specimen.  These rifles have evolved from the very common Russian Mosin Nagant M91/30 when they were captured by the Germans and sold to the Fins.  The extrinsic value of this gun can range from $350-500 before fees.  It's the intrinsic value of this PPARICULAR un that makes it such a hot item.  To be honest, I'm just as happy to keep it and pass it down my family line.  

I learned that the Russion M91/30 numbered between 13,000,000-14,000,000.  Total production of the M39 rifle during wartime period of 1940-1945 was a total of 96,800 rifles.  Total production of the M39 including post-war modifications is approimately 102,000.  Needless to say, this rifle is quite rare these days.  

The gun has the typical hexagonal Russion reciever with an R for Remington.  The major markings on the barrel shank are
SA                    boxed SA indicating Finnish Regular Army
VKT                  later logo
D                      reworked for Finnish D166 cartridge
34905               serial number has no prefixes or suffixes
1941                 year of production

One characteristic noted from observed specimens and from the database of registerred rifles of VKT and Belgian barreled M39s is that the dates on the barrels are not chronological in the order of the serial numbers.  This raise the possibility that the barrels were not date stamped until they were actulaly assembled at AV3.  Of the 30,300 reported barrels that used VKT and Belgian specimens, it appears that 1943 dated VKT barreled rifles are quite scarce and that Belgian produced barrels as used on the M39s are rare as well.  An educated guiss by analysis of known serial numbers and determination of barrels produced apparently in sequence can be ventured as to total numbers of guns produced.

This specific gun is a WARTIME gun.  It has war-time pistol grip stock with war-time stock splices.  The stock is made by Lindholmin Puusepantehdas using the stock marker's cartouche of an "L" in the circle.

The buttplate has had all markings rubbed off. 

The Russian symbols include the Izhevsk Bow and Arrow in front of the magazine plate and on the bolt assembly.  The magazine floor plate number has the last four serial numbers 4905.

Interestingly enough, there is also the Tula Hammer symbol on the Cocking Knob.

It also appears to have a faded Tula Hammer within a circle on the bolt body.  The bolt's number is also 4905.

There are other symbols by the bolt body and cocking knob that I can't identify yet.

Lastly, Finnish M28/30s and M39s have sight graduations on the side of the rear sight base that are often mistaken for serial numbers by new Mosin Nagant collectors. 86432.

I'm hoping to snag one more before the end of the year, so I'll keep updating.  More pictures available upon request.

title: For Sale:  Bumpfire Stock
postcontent:
Up for grabs is a lightly used Bumpfire Stock.  These allow you to simulate full-auto in a completely legal, BATF-approved manner with no need for a stamp, tax, or registration.  Just unscrew your grip from your AR lower (mind the detent spring), screw in the receiver block, slip on the stock, attach your upper and start having fun!  

Once you get the hang of it (you need to apply steady forward pressure) you can unload your 30 round mags in about 3-4 seconds!  Or control your bursts at your own discretion.  Recommend using a carbine gas system upper and installing a muzzle break.  Once I did, it was easy to keep on target.  This thing is guaranteed to put a smile on your face!

I ran fewer than 300 rounds with it, but decided to sell the AR for something different.  SALE IS FOR THE BUMPFIRE STOCK ONLY (The lower receiver and the strap in the pictures are for REFERENCE ONLY and is NOT INCLUDED with the stock--sold them already).

Must be at least 21.  Cash only; no Sunday sales.  Willing to ship it for an additional $7 (payment via DISCRETE PayPal (no mention of firearms related stuff; no fees option or add 3.5%) or PMO only).

title: For Sale:  Quarter Circle 10 lower receiver - Glock compatible
postcontent:
Glock Small Frame (multi-cal) 9mm, 357 Sig and .40 S&W compatible.  Considered one of the premier pistol caliber AR manufacturers in the U.S.  Features the unique Last Round Bolt Hold Open (LRBHO) function not found on most blow back designs.
>> Not interested in trades at this time <<

https://www.quartercircle10.com/   

This is our Glock Small Frame model. With our lower we didn’t cut any corners, these lowers are not just another forged AR15 lower cut for glock magazines. These lowers were designed with not only function in mind but aesthetics and it makes our lowers the perfect platform for shooting small frame glock magazines. These lowers are manufactured by us at our facility in Tucson, Arizona.  They are CNC machined from 7075 aluminum in house on our machines. They will accept all Glock 9mm, 357 Sig and .40 S&W magazines. These lowers were designed for the purpose of engaging targets beyond pistol ranges. This is the perfect platform for any tactical application or just a fun day at the range.

With just a change of your bolt and barrel you can go switch between 3 different calibers all with the same lower and upper. Having one of our Pistol Caliber Carbines and a handgun that shoots the same round enables shooters to carry one type of ammunition, and feed both guns from one magazine. Running short on one type of ammo doesn’t happen; both guns stay in the fight until the last round is gone. The concept is not unique to modern times. Lawmen in the Old West sometimes carried revolvers that chambered the same rounds as their trusty lever-action rifles. Maintaining only one kind of cartridge made sense to a lot of men on the trail back then, just as it still does for many officers and civilians on the street today.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Smith & Wesson  28-2 HIGHWAY PATROLMAN "S" 1965  .357 MAGNUM
postcontent: Smith & Wesson model 28-2 Hwy Patrolman.This revolver is chambered for .357 magnum cartridges. Comes with the 6" pinned barrel and a six round recessed cylinder. The barrel ends are fantastic and there is very little holster wear and some slight freckling from storage. This gun has a serial number of S243XXX and has been researched to be manufactured in 1965. The gun is in very nice condition for being fifty years old. The Eagle target grips are relieved, and they come with silver medallions. They show very nicely and the rich wood contrasts beautifully with the bead blasted top strap and blue frame finish. The finish on all the model 28's top straps have been bead blasted to deflect any glare in bright conditions. The condition of the bluing is very well preserved with only the most limited signs of age. Smith & Wesson released this model as a lesser option variant of the 27 and quickly became a favorite among service personnel and those in the line of duty. This 28-2 also features the checkered  semi Target Hammer with a serrated Trigger and both have been finished with distinctive case hardened coloring. If you ever had the desire to add one of these to your collection of fine iron, I got a 6" for your consideration. All engineered mechanics on this model 28-2 function perfectly, and as with all Smith & Wesson revolvers of this generation, she comes pinned and recessed. This revolver carries a very rich tradition and has a strong following by those individuals that were looking for function over form. All business all day long. This highway Patrolman honors all those American servicemen and women who dedicated so much in the line of duty. $650 OBO

The Rogers Super-Stoc™ (commonly called the Super Stock) is the ultimate refinement in AR/M4 stock technology. The Rogers Super-Stoc™ is the most stable, collapsible stock available due to the innovative cam-lock system developed by Bill Rogers, famed shooting instructor, inventor of holsters, target systems, and other related products, and his staff of engineers. The cam-lock system completely removes any slop or play inherent with collapsible stocks. title: For Sale:  M1 Garand HRA
postcontent: a beautiful rifle in almost like issued condition. This M1 Garand rifle) was manufactured in mid 1955. The receiver is 6528291. The barrel is marked HRA 6535448 1-55 RS46 PM. The TE is 2 and the MW is 1+. The barrel has distinct lands and grooves and is shiny. The bolt is 6528287 HRA U and the op rod is D35382 9 SA. The gas cylinder lock has no hump. The front sight is 5/8" wide. The trigger group is all Springfield with the trigger assembly number 6528290-14-SA and the hammer C65546008-5 SA. The safety is C46015-9SA. The finish on the metal is very good estimate 99% of new. The rear sights look and feel new. The elevation knob is NFC, windage knob is marked SA. The stock is a USGI issue in walnut with the stamp on the left side by the rear sight and the circle P double stamped on the grip.. It is solid and has few handling marks. This rifle is in exceptional condition. I have fired this rifle and it functions extremely well. This is a beautiful rifle as well as a great addition to your collection

title: For Sale:  Diamondback 380 Pink Pistol
postcontent:
Looking for a micro-compact .380 automatic pistol that's built entirely in the USA? Consider the Diamondback DB380! This striker fired semi automatic pistol is designed with safety in mind, from it's "Zero Energy" striker system to a mechanical firing pin bloce. The magazine catch is steel and secures a sheet metal magazine holding six rounds. Almost unheard of in a sub-compact pistol, the DB380 even sports windage-adjustable sights.

The FEA (Finite Element Analysis) designed slide and barrel are stronger than any comparable firearm, resulting in durability with less felt recoil, and the absence of removable pins or tools makes field stripping easier than ever. The slide, barrel and internal parts are coated to resist corrosion, making this pistol a lifetime investment.
